Universal AGI via Semantic Fixed‑Point Theory.

Author: Ouadi Maakoul

Date: April 2026

---

Abstract

We present a rigorous mathematical framework for Artificial General Intelligence (AGI) based on fixed‑point theory in semantic quotient spaces. Intelligence is defined as the convergence of a recursive cognitive operator to a unique semantic fixed point under intent constraints. Using a semi‑Fredholm semantic projection, we construct a complete metric space that is well‑behaved even in infinite dimensions. The cognitive operator is the composition of an improvement map and a compression map; we prove convergence using local contraction (Ostrowski’s theorem) rather than global Lipschitz conditions, allowing for realistic neural network behaviour. Stochastic cognitive operators are analysed via Doob’s martingale convergence theorem, yielding almost‑sure convergence. Alignment stability is quantified by the condition number of the resolvent (I - DR)^{-1}, showing that near‑identity operators cause catastrophic fragility. Edge cases (divergence, semantic collapse, indecisive AGI) are characterised using non‑expansive mapping theory. All theorems are presented with descriptive names; contributions from collaborative AI systems are acknowledged.

