3. Semantic Space Construction

3.1 Semantic Feature Map

Let S be a complete metric space representing all possible internal and external system states. Fix an intent I \in \mathcal{I}, where \mathcal{I} is a Riemannian manifold (e.g., a space of goal vectors or utility functions). Let \mathcal{H} be a separable Hilbert space (the semantic feature space).

Definition 3.1 (Semantic projection).
Let \Phi_I: S \to \mathcal{H} be a uniformly continuous map. We assume that \Phi_I is Frèchet differentiable on an open set containing the relevant trajectories, and that its derivative D\Phi_I(s) at each point is a semi‑Fredholm operator with finite‑dimensional kernel. This ensures:

· The image \mathcal{R}_I := \Phi_I(S) is closed in \mathcal{H} (by the semi‑Fredholm property).
· The “information loss” when projecting to semantics is finite‑dimensional – a natural condition for neural networks that compress high‑dimensional inputs into low‑dimensional representations.

Computational instantiation. In practice, \Phi_I can be realised as a deep neural network with a linear output layer, regularised so that the Jacobian has constant rank (e.g., via spectral normalisation and rank‑aware penalties).

3.2 Semantic Equivalence and Quotient Space

Define a pseudo‑metric on S by

d_I(s,t) := \|\Phi_I(s) - \Phi_I(t)\|_{\mathcal{H}}.

Two states are semantically equivalent under intent I if they produce the same semantic features:

s \sim_I t \iff \Phi_I(s) = \Phi_I(t) \iff d_I(s,t)=0.

Definition 3.2 (Semantic quotient space).
Let Q_I := S / \sim_I be the set of equivalence classes [s]. Define the metric

d_I([s],[t]) := \|\Phi_I(s) - \Phi_I(t)\|_{\mathcal{H}}.

This is well‑defined because it does not depend on the choice of representatives.

Theorem 3.1 (Gemini Completeness Theorem).
(Q_I, d_I) is a complete metric space. Moreover, it is isometric to the closed set \mathcal{R}_I \subseteq \mathcal{H}.

Proof. Define \Psi: Q_I \to \mathcal{H} by \Psi([s]) = \Phi_I(s).

· Well‑definedness: If [s]=[t] then \Phi_I(s)=\Phi_I(t), so \Psi([s])=\Psi([t]).
· Injectivity: \Psi([s])=\Psi([t]) implies \Phi_I(s)=\Phi_I(t), hence [s]=[t].
· Isometry: d_I([s],[t]) = \|\Phi_I(s)-\Phi_I(t)\|_{\mathcal{H}} = \|\Psi([s])-\Psi([t])\|_{\mathcal{H}}.
· Image: \Psi(Q_I) = \Phi_I(S) = \mathcal{R}_I, which is closed because \Phi_I is semi‑Fredholm (closed range property).
· Completeness: \mathcal{H} is complete, so any closed subset is complete. An isometry preserves completeness, therefore Q_I is complete. ∎

Remark. The semi‑Fredholm condition is essential in infinite dimensions. Without it, \mathcal{R}_I could be non‑closed (e.g., the image of a compact operator with infinite‑dimensional range), making Q_I non‑complete. In finite dimensions, every linear map has closed range, so the condition is automatically satisfied.

