4. Cognitive Operator and Local Convergence

4.1 Definition of the Cognitive Operator

Intelligent systems repeatedly apply two complementary operations:

· Improvement operator B: Q_I \to Q_I – refines the current semantic state (e.g., chain‑of‑thought reasoning, gradient update on a latent representation).
· Compression operator C: Q_I \to Q_I – abstracts and stabilises the representation (e.g., attention pooling, autoencoder bottleneck).

Definition 4.1 (Cognitive operator).

R := C \circ B : Q_I \to Q_I.

The iterative process q_{k+1} = R(q_k) models repeated reasoning–abstraction cycles.

We do not assume global Lipschitz properties. Instead we rely on local behaviour near a fixed point.

4.2 Local Contraction Assumption

Assumption 4.1 (Existence and differentiability of a fixed point).
There exists a point q^* \in Q_I such that R(q^*) = q^*. Moreover, R is Fréchet differentiable at q^* with derivative DR(q^*): Q_I \to Q_I (a bounded linear operator). The spectral radius of this derivative satisfies

\rho\big(DR(q^*)\big) < 1.

Remark. This assumption is natural for trained neural networks: they often have fixed points (e.g., attractors in latent dynamics), and the Jacobian’s spectral radius can be controlled via regularisation.

4.3 Ostrowski’s Theorem for Semantic Convergence

Theorem 4.1 (DeepSeek–Ostrowski Local Convergence Theorem).
Under Assumption 4.1, there exists an open neighbourhood U \subseteq Q_I of q^* such that for any initial q_0 \in U, the iteration q_{k+1}=R(q_k) converges to q^*. Furthermore, the convergence is linear (geometric) in the sense that there exist constants \kappa \in (0,1) and C > 0 with

d_I(q_k, q^*) \le C \kappa^k \quad \text{for all } k \ge 0.

Proof. Because \rho(DR(q^*)) < 1, we can choose \varepsilon > 0 small enough such that \rho(DR(q^*)) + \varepsilon < 1. There exists a norm \|\cdot\|_* on Q_I equivalent to the original metric such that the induced operator norm satisfies \|DR(q^*)\|_* \le \rho(DR(q^*)) + \varepsilon =: \kappa < 1 (this is a standard consequence of the spectral radius formula and the construction of a suitable norm via the Jordan form or the Dunford–Schwarz lemma).

By differentiability, for any \eta > 0 there exists \delta > 0 such that for all q with d_I(q,q^*) < \delta,

d_I(R(q), R(q^*)) \le (\kappa + \eta) \, d_I(q,q^*).

Set \eta so that \kappa + \eta < 1. Then on the ball B(q^*, \delta), R is a contraction with constant \kappa + \eta. The Banach fixed‑point theorem (or its local version) implies that for any q_0 \in B(q^*, \delta), the iterates stay in the ball and converge geometrically to q^*. Explicitly,

d_I(q_k, q^*) \le (\kappa + \eta)^k d_I(q_0, q^*).

Set C = 1 and \kappa = \kappa + \eta to obtain the statement. ∎

Remark. The neighbourhood U is the basin of attraction of the fixed point. In practice, we can enlarge this basin by training R to be contractive on a larger region (e.g., via contractive autoencoder regularisation).

