6. Alignment Stability: Resolvent Condition Number

Alignment refers to the property that the AGI’s behaviour remains consistent with a human‑specified intent, even when the intent is perturbed slightly. We quantify this via the sensitivity of the fixed point with respect to intent parameters.

6.1 Intent Parameterisation

Let the intent I be parameterised by a vector \theta \in \mathbb{R}^d (e.g., a point on a low‑dimensional manifold). Write R_\theta for the cognitive operator, and assume it has a unique fixed point q^*(\theta) satisfying q^*(\theta) = R_\theta(q^*(\theta)). Assume R_\theta is Fréchet differentiable in both the state and the parameter, with DR_\theta(q^*(\theta)) denoting the derivative with respect to the state.

6.2 Linearised Sensitivity

Differentiating the fixed‑point equation with respect to \theta gives (using the chain rule)

\frac{\partial q^*}{\partial \theta} = DR_\theta(q^*) \frac{\partial q^*}{\partial \theta} + \frac{\partial R_\theta}{\partial \theta}(q^*).

Rearranging,

\big(I - DR_\theta(q^*)\big) \frac{\partial q^*}{\partial \theta} = \frac{\partial R_\theta}{\partial \theta}(q^*).

Definition 6.1 (Resolvent and condition number).
Let A_\theta := I - DR_\theta(q^*). Since \rho(DR_\theta(q^*)) < 1 (by the local contraction assumption), the Neumann series \sum_{n=0}^\infty (DR_\theta)^n converges and A_\theta is invertible. The condition number of the alignment problem is

\kappa(A_\theta) := \|A_\theta\| \cdot \|A_\theta^{-1}\|.

Theorem 6.1 (Ouadi Alignment Fragility Theorem).
The sensitivity of the fixed point to intent changes is bounded by

\left\| \frac{\partial q^*}{\partial \theta} \right\| \le \|A_\theta^{-1}\| \cdot \left\| \frac{\partial R_\theta}{\partial \theta} \right\|.

In particular, if \rho(DR_\theta(q^*)) is close to 1, then \|A_\theta^{-1}\| becomes large (because the smallest singular value of A_\theta is 1 - \rho(DR_\theta) up to constants), and even small perturbations in \theta can cause large changes in q^*. This is alignment fragility: a nearly non‑contractive AGI is not safely alignable.

Proof. From the linearised equation,

\frac{\partial q^*}{\partial \theta} = A_\theta^{-1} \frac{\partial R_\theta}{\partial \theta}(q^*).

Taking norms and using the sub‑multiplicativity of the operator norm yields the bound. The remark about \rho(DR_\theta) follows from the fact that \|A_\theta^{-1}\| \ge 1 / (1 - \|DR_\theta\|) \ge 1 / (1 - \rho(DR_\theta) - \varepsilon) for any \varepsilon>0 when the operator is normal; for non‑normal operators, the pseudospectrum can cause even larger sensitivity. ∎

Corollary 6.2 (Safe alignability condition).
For an AGI to be robustly alignable, there must exist a uniform bound M < \infty such that \|(I - DR_\theta)^{-1}\| \le M for all admissible intents \theta. This is equivalent to requiring that the spectral radius of DR_\theta is bounded away from 1 uniformly in \theta.

