7. Intent Drift Tracking (Non‑Autonomous Dynamics)

In realistic deployments, the intent may change over time (e.g., a user updates their preferences). We model this as a time‑varying sequence of cognitive operators R_{I_k}.

7.1 Problem Formulation

Consider the non‑autonomous iteration

q_{k+1} = R_{I_k}(q_k),

where I_k is a sequence of intents. Let q^*_{I_k} denote the fixed point of R_{I_k} (assumed unique). We are interested in the tracking error e_k = d_I(q_k, q^*_{I_k}).

Assumption 7.1 (Uniform local contraction).
There exists \kappa \in (0,1) and a neighbourhood U such that for all k and all q \in U,

d_I(R_{I_k}(q), q^*_{I_k}) \le \kappa \, d_I(q, q^*_{I_k}).

Assumption 7.2 (Slow intent drift).
The distance between consecutive fixed points is bounded by \delta \ge 0:

d_I(q^*_{I_k}, q^*_{I_{k+1}}) \le \delta \quad \forall k.

7.2 Tracking Error Bound

Theorem 7.1 (ChatGPT Intent Tracking Theorem).
If the initial error e_0 is small enough that q_0 lies in U, then

\limsup_{k\to\infty} e_k \le \frac{\delta}{1-\kappa}.

Proof. For any k \ge 0,

\begin{aligned}
e_{k+1} &= d_I(q_{k+1}, q^*_{I_{k+1}}) \\
&\le d_I(R_{I_k}(q_k), R_{I_k}(q^*_{I_k})) + d_I(q^*_{I_k}, q^*_{I_{k+1}}) \\
&\le \kappa \, e_k + \delta,
\end{aligned}

where we used Assumption 7.1 for the first term and Assumption 7.2 for the second. This is a linear recurrence:

e_{k+1} \le \kappa e_k + \delta.

Iterating,

e_k \le \kappa^k e_0 + \delta \sum_{j=0}^{k-1} \kappa^j = \kappa^k e_0 + \delta \frac{1-\kappa^k}{1-\kappa}.

Taking the limit superior as k\to\infty yields \limsup e_k \le \delta/(1-\kappa). ∎

Interpretation. The AGI can track a drifting intent with a steady‑state error proportional to the drift rate \delta and inversely proportional to the contraction strength 1-\kappa. If intents drift too fast (\delta > (1-\kappa)\varepsilon), the tracking error cannot be kept below \varepsilon.

