8. Edge Cases and Failure Modes

8.1 Divergence

If \rho(DR(q^*)) \ge 1 (or no fixed point exists), the iteration may diverge, oscillate, or exhibit chaos. This corresponds to an AGI that cannot stabilise its reasoning – it either explodes or wanders indefinitely.

8.2 Semantic Collapse

If the compression operator C is too aggressive, it may map distinct semantic classes to the same point, effectively losing information. Formally, if there is no lower Lipschitz bound on C (i.e., \inf_{q\neq q'} \frac{d(C(q),C(q'))}{d(q,q')} = 0), then the fixed point can be trivial (e.g., zero vector) even when the intent is non‑trivial. We avoid this by requiring a bi‑Lipschitz condition on C:

\gamma \, d(q,q') \le d(C(q), C(q')) \le \beta \, d(q,q'), \quad \gamma > 0.

This ensures that compression preserves semantic distinctions.

8.3 Indecisive AGI (Non‑Expansive Case)

If R is non‑expansive (\mathrm{Lip}(R) \le 1) but not a contraction, the Browder–Göhde–Kirk theorem guarantees existence of a fixed point when Q_I is bounded, closed, and convex. However, uniqueness fails – the AGI may have multiple stable interpretations and could oscillate among them. This models an “indecisive” system that never settles on a single meaning.

