10. Conclusion

We have presented a rigorous, publication‑ready mathematical framework for AGI as convergence to a semantic fixed point. Key formal contributions:

· Topological completeness using semi‑Fredholm operators (closed range, finite‑dimensional kernel) – Gemini Completeness Theorem.
· Local contraction via Ostrowski’s theorem, removing global Lipschitz assumptions – DeepSeek–Ostrowski Local Convergence Theorem.
· Almost‑sure stochastic convergence using Doob’s martingale theorem, stronger than convergence in mean – Grok–Doob Almost‑Sure Convergence Theorem.
· Alignment fragility quantified by the condition number of the resolvent (I - DR)^{-1} – Ouadi Alignment Fragility Theorem.
· Intent drift tracking with explicit error bounds – ChatGPT Intent Tracking Theorem.
· Edge cases (divergence, collapse, indecisiveness) characterised via non‑expansive mapping theory.

This framework transforms the notion of “stable intelligence” into a testable mathematical law. Future work includes:

· Constructing explicit semi‑Fredholm projections for large language models (e.g., via low‑rank adapters).
· Empirical validation of the condition number bound on current LLMs under recursive prompting.
