Appendix A: Functional Analysis Background

This appendix provides a self‑contained review of the functional analytic concepts used in the main text.

A.1 Banach and Hilbert Spaces

Definition A.1 (Banach space). A Banach space (X, \|\cdot\|) is a complete normed vector space over \mathbb{R} or \mathbb{C}. Completeness means that every Cauchy sequence converges to a limit in X.

Definition A.2 (Hilbert space). A Hilbert space \mathcal{H} is a Banach space whose norm is induced by an inner product: \|x\| = \sqrt{\langle x, x \rangle}. The inner product provides notions of orthogonality and projection.

A.2 Linear Operators

Definition A.3 (Bounded linear operator). A linear map T: X \to Y between normed spaces is bounded if there exists C \ge 0 such that \|Tx\|_Y \le C \|x\|_X for all x \in X. The operator norm is \|T\| = \sup_{\|x\|=1} \|Tx\|_Y.

Definition A.4 (Closed range). T has closed range if T(X) is a closed subspace of Y. This is equivalent to the existence of a constant c>0 such that \|Tx\| \ge c \|x\| for all x \in (\ker T)^\perp when T is bounded and X,Y are Banach (by the closed range theorem).

Definition A.5 (Semi‑Fredholm operator). A bounded linear operator T: X \to Y is semi‑Fredholm if it has closed range and either \dim \ker T < \infty (type F_+) or \dim \operatorname{coker} T < \infty (type F_-). In this paper we only need the F_+ case.

Theorem A.6 (Closed range theorem). For a bounded linear operator T: X \to Y between Banach spaces, the following are equivalent: (i) T(X) is closed; (ii) T is bounded below on (\ker T)^\perp; (iii) the adjoint T^* has closed range.

A.3 Quotient Spaces

Let X be a Banach space and M \subseteq X a closed subspace. Define an equivalence relation x \sim y \iff x-y \in M. The quotient space X/M consists of equivalence classes [x] = x+M. The quotient norm is

\|[x]\|_{X/M} = \inf_{m \in M} \|x - m\|_X.

(X/M, \|\cdot\|_{X/M}) is a Banach space. If T: X \to Y is bounded linear with \ker T = M and T(X) closed, then the induced map \tilde{T}: X/M \to T(X) is an isomorphism onto its image.

A.4 Spectral Radius

Definition A.7 (Spectral radius). For a bounded linear operator T on a Banach space, the spectral radius is

\rho(T) = \lim_{n\to\infty} \|T^n\|^{1/n} = \sup\{|\lambda| : \lambda \in \sigma(T)\},

where \sigma(T) is the spectrum. For finite‑dimensional spaces, \rho(T) = \max |\lambda_i| over eigenvalues.

Lemma A.8 (Approximation of spectral radius). For any \varepsilon > 0 there exists a norm \|\cdot\|_\varepsilon equivalent to the original norm such that \|T\|_\varepsilon \le \rho(T) + \varepsilon.

A.5 Fréchet Derivative

Definition A.9 (Fréchet derivative). Let F: X \to Y be a map between Banach spaces. F is Fréchet differentiable at x_0 if there exists a bounded linear operator DF(x_0): X \to Y such that

\lim_{\|h\|\to 0} \frac{\|F(x_0+h) - F(x_0) - DF(x_0)h\|_Y}{\|h\|_X} = 0.

The operator DF(x_0) is the Fréchet derivative.

