Appendix B: Proof of Gemini Completeness Theorem (Alternative)

Theorem B.1 (Gemini Completeness Theorem – restated).
Let \Phi_I: S \to \mathcal{H} be uniformly continuous with closed image \mathcal{R}_I. Then (Q_I, d_I) is a complete metric space isometric to \mathcal{R}_I.

Proof (using the closed graph theorem for the isometry). Define \Psi: Q_I \to \mathcal{R}_I by \Psi([s]) = \Phi_I(s).

· Well‑defined and injective: As in the main proof.
· Surjective: By definition of \mathcal{R}_I.
· Isometric: d_I([s],[t]) = \|\Phi_I(s)-\Phi_I(t)\|_{\mathcal{H}} = \|\Psi([s])-\Psi([t])\|_{\mathcal{H}}.

Now consider the inverse map \Psi^{-1}: \mathcal{R}_I \to Q_I. We claim \Psi^{-1} is continuous. Indeed, if \Phi_I(s_n) \to \Phi_I(s) in \mathcal{H}, then d_I([s_n],[s]) \to 0, so [s_n] \to [s] in Q_I. Hence \Psi^{-1} is continuous (in fact, an isometry). Since \mathcal{R}_I is closed in \mathcal{H}, it is complete. The isometry \Psi then transfers completeness to Q_I. ∎

Remark. The closedness of \mathcal{R}_I is crucial. A standard counterexample: let \mathcal{H} = \ell^2, and let \Phi_I: \ell^2 \to \ell^2 be the map \Phi_I(x) = (x_1, x_2/2, x_3/3, \dots). This operator is compact and injective, but its image is not closed (it is dense but not all of \ell^2). Then Q_I would be isometric to a non‑closed subset of \ell^2, hence incomplete – a pathological semantic space.

