Appendix D: Stochastic Convergence Details

D.1 Martingale Background

Definition D.1 (Filtration, martingale). Let (\Omega, \mathcal{F}, P) be a probability space. A filtration \{\mathcal{F}_k\}_{k\ge 0} is an increasing sequence of sub‑σ‑algebras. A sequence \{e_k\} is adapted if e_k is \mathcal{F}_k-measurable. It is a super‑martingale if \mathbb{E}[|e_k|] < \infty and \mathbb{E}[e_{k+1} \mid \mathcal{F}_k] \le e_k a.s.

Theorem D.2 (Doob’s martingale convergence theorem). If \{e_k\} is a non‑negative super‑martingale, then e_k converges almost surely to a finite limit e_\infty.

D.2 Proof of the Grok–Doob Theorem (expanded)

We restate the theorem with explicit notation.

Theorem D.3 (Grok–Doob Almost‑Sure Convergence Theorem).
Let (\Omega, \mathcal{F}, P) be a probability space, \{\mathcal{F}_k\} a filtration. Let \{q_k\} be defined by q_{k+1} = R_{\omega_k}(q_k), where R_{\omega_k} are random operators with a common fixed point q^* (i.e., R_{\omega_k}(q^*) = q^* a.s.). Suppose there exists \kappa \in (0,1) and a neighbourhood U such that for all q \in U,

\mathbb{E}[d_I(R_\omega(q), q^*)^2 \mid \mathcal{F}_k] \le \kappa^2 d_I(q, q^*)^2 \quad \text{a.s.}

If q_0 \in U a.s., then q_k \to q^* almost surely.

Proof. Set e_k = d_I(q_k, q^*)^2.

· Adaptedness: q_k is \mathcal{F}_k-measurable, hence e_k is \mathcal{F}_k-measurable.
· Super‑martingale: By the contraction assumption,
  \mathbb{E}[e_{k+1} \mid \mathcal{F}_k] = \mathbb{E}[d_I(R_{\omega_k}(q_k), q^*)^2 \mid \mathcal{F}_k] \le \kappa^2 e_k \le e_k \quad \text{a.s.}
  Moreover, e_k \ge 0 and \mathbb{E}[e_k] \le \kappa^{2k} \mathbb{E}[e_0] < \infty.
· Almost‑sure convergence: Doob’s theorem gives e_k \to e_\infty a.s. for some random variable e_\infty \ge 0.
· Limit is zero: From \mathbb{E}[e_{k+1}] \le \kappa^2 \mathbb{E}[e_k], we get \mathbb{E}[e_k] \to 0. By Fatou’s lemma,
  \mathbb{E}[e_\infty] = \mathbb{E}[\liminf_{k\to\infty} e_k] \le \liminf_{k\to\infty} \mathbb{E}[e_k] = 0.
  Since e_\infty \ge 0 a.s., this forces e_\infty = 0 a.s. Hence d_I(q_k, q^*) \to 0 a.s. ∎

Remark. The theorem does not require the maps R_{\omega_k} to be contractions individually; only the expected squared contraction matters. This is crucial for noisy neural network updates where a single step may be expansive, but on average the system contracts.

