Appendix E: Condition Number and Perturbation Theory

E.1 Resolvent and Neumann Series

Lemma E.1 (Neumann series). If T is a bounded linear operator on a Banach space with \|T\| < 1, then I - T is invertible and

(I - T)^{-1} = \sum_{n=0}^\infty T^n,

with \|(I - T)^{-1}\| \le \frac{1}{1 - \|T\|}.

Proof. Standard: the series converges absolutely because \sum \|T\|^n = 1/(1-\|T\|). Multiplying (I-T)\sum_{n=0}^N T^n = I - T^{N+1} \to I. ∎

Corollary E.2 (Bound on inverse norm). Under the same condition,

\|(I - T)^{-1}\| \ge \frac{1}{1 + \|T\|} \quad \text{(lower bound not generally useful)}.

More importantly, the condition number \kappa(I-T) = \|I-T\| \cdot \|(I-T)^{-1}\| can be large even when \|T\| is close to 1.

E.2 Sensitivity of Fixed Points

Consider a parameter‑dependent contraction R_\theta with fixed point q^*(\theta). Differentiating q^*(\theta) = R_\theta(q^*(\theta)) yields

\frac{\partial q^*}{\partial \theta} = \frac{\partial R_\theta}{\partial \theta}(q^*) + DR_\theta(q^*) \frac{\partial q^*}{\partial \theta}.

Hence

\frac{\partial q^*}{\partial \theta} = (I - DR_\theta(q^*))^{-1} \frac{\partial R_\theta}{\partial \theta}(q^*).

Theorem E.3 (Ouadi Alignment Fragility – quantitative bound).
For any direction v in parameter space,

\left\| \frac{\partial q^*}{\partial \theta} v \right\| \le \|(I - DR_\theta)^{-1}\| \cdot \left\| \frac{\partial R_\theta}{\partial \theta} v \right\|.

Moreover, if DR_\theta is normal (or if we consider the worst‑case direction), then

\|(I - DR_\theta)^{-1}\| = \frac{1}{\min_{\lambda \in \sigma(DR_\theta)} |1 - \lambda|} \ge \frac{1}{1 - \rho(DR_\theta)}.

Proof. The first bound is immediate from the operator norm. For the second, when DR_\theta is normal, its eigenvalues are \lambda_i and the eigenvalues of (I - DR_\theta)^{-1} are 1/(1-\lambda_i). The norm equals the maximum of |1/(1-\lambda_i)| = 1/|1-\lambda_i|. The smallest denominator occurs when \lambda_i is closest to 1, which is at most \rho(DR_\theta) if the spectral radius is attained. Thus \|(I - DR_\theta)^{-1}\| \ge 1/(1 - \rho(DR_\theta)). ∎

Implication for alignment. To keep the fixed point insensitive to intent changes, we need \rho(DR_\theta) bounded away from 1 uniformly over admissible intents. Otherwise, the condition number diverges and arbitrarily small intent perturbations can cause arbitrarily large changes in the AGI’s stable state.

