Appendix F: Neural Network Realisation of Semi‑Fredholm Projections

F.1 Constant‑Rank Jacobian Regularisation

Let \Phi_I: \mathbb{R}^d \to \mathbb{R}^m be a neural network. The derivative D\Phi_I(s) is a m \times d matrix. For \Phi_I to be semi‑Fredholm (with finite‑dimensional kernel), we need the Jacobian to have constant rank r \le \min(d,m) on the set of states of interest. This ensures that the image is locally a submanifold of dimension r, and the kernel has dimension d-r.

Regularisation loss:

\mathcal{L}_{\text{rank}} = \lambda \cdot \mathbb{E}_{s \sim \text{data}} \left[ \sum_{i=r+1}^{\min(d,m)} \sigma_i(J(s))^2 \right],

where \sigma_i(J) are the singular values. This penalises the (r+1)-th singular value, encouraging the Jacobian to have rank at most r. To enforce exactly rank r, one can use a manifold‑aware training (e.g., via projection onto the set of constant‑rank matrices).

F.2 Closed Range via Spectral Normalisation

For a linear layer W, the range is closed automatically. For non‑linear maps, closedness of the global image is subtle. A sufficient condition is that \Phi_I is proper (preimages of compact sets are compact) and injective on a closed subset. In practice, we rely on the fact that neural networks with bounded weights and smooth activations map compact domains to compact sets; if the input space S is compact (e.g., a bounded region in \mathbb{R}^d), then \Phi_I(S) is compact, hence closed.

F.3 Practical Construction for LLMs

For a large language model, we can define \Phi_I as the output of a certain layer (e.g., the last hidden state) projected onto a low‑dimensional subspace via a learned linear map W_I. The low‑dimensional projection ensures finite‑dimensional kernel (the nullspace of W_I composed with the layer). By regularising W_I to be of full rank r (with r small), we obtain a semi‑Fredholm projection with closed range.

