Appendix H: Additional Lemmas and Corollaries

Lemma H.1 (Stability of fixed points under small perturbations).
Let R and \tilde{R} be two contractions on a complete metric space with fixed points q^* and \tilde{q}^*. If \sup_{x} d(R(x), \tilde{R}(x)) \le \varepsilon, then

d(q^*, \tilde{q}^*) \le \frac{\varepsilon}{1 - \max(\kappa, \tilde{\kappa})},

where \kappa, \tilde{\kappa} are the contraction constants.

Proof. Using the fixed‑point equations and the triangle inequality,

d(q^*, \tilde{q}^*) \le d(R(q^*), \tilde{R}(q^*)) + d(\tilde{R}(q^*), \tilde{R}(\tilde{q}^*)) \le \varepsilon + \tilde{\kappa} d(q^*, \tilde{q}^*).

Hence (1-\tilde{\kappa}) d(q^*, \tilde{q}^*) \le \varepsilon. Symmetrically, we can replace \tilde{\kappa} by \kappa to get the bound. ∎

Corollary H.2 (Alignment under bounded intent change).
If two intents I, I' yield cognitive operators R_I, R_{I'} that are uniformly close (\sup_q d(R_I(q), R_{I'}(q)) \le \varepsilon), then the distance between their fixed points is bounded by \varepsilon/(1-\kappa) where \kappa is the maximum contraction constant. This provides an alternative, simpler alignment bound to Theorem 6.1, though less tight.

Lemma H.3 (Convergence rate for Meir–Keeler contractions).
While Meir–Keeler contractions need not have a uniform contraction factor, they still converge. Moreover, the convergence is eventually faster than any geometric rate with factor <1: for any \rho \in (0,1), there exists K such that for all k \ge K, d(q_k, q^*) \le \rho^{k-K} d(q_K, q^*). This is proven by showing that the sequence of distances eventually decreases by a factor at most \rho once it falls below a certain threshold.

