Appendix I: Example – Linear Cognitive Operator

To illustrate the theory, consider a simple linear model on \mathbb{R}^n. Let Q_I = \mathbb{R}^n, B = \alpha \cdot \mathrm{Id} (improvement scales by \alpha), C = \beta \cdot \mathrm{Id} (compression scales by \beta), with 0 < \alpha\beta < 1. Then R(q) = \alpha\beta q. The unique fixed point is q^* = 0. The iteration converges geometrically: q_k = (\alpha\beta)^k q_0. The derivative DR = \alpha\beta I, so \rho(DR) = \alpha\beta. The condition number of alignment is \kappa(I - DR) = \frac{1+\alpha\beta}{1-\alpha\beta}, which grows as (\alpha\beta) \to 1. This matches the fragility result: when \alpha\beta is close to 1, even a small change in \alpha or \beta (i.e., in the “intent” to scale) leads to a large change in the fixed point? Actually, in this linear example the fixed point is always zero, so sensitivity is zero. To see non‑trivial sensitivity, add an affine term: R(q) = \kappa q + b, with 0 \le \kappa < 1. Then q^* = b/(1-\kappa). The derivative DR = \kappa I, and \kappa(I - DR) = \frac{1+\kappa}{1-\kappa}. The sensitivity \partial q^*/\partial b = 1/(1-\kappa) which is large when \kappa is close to 1. This illustrates that the condition number of I-DR directly controls sensitivity to perturbations in the constant term, which can be interpreted as a change in intent.

